<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n09117j"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n09" href="#n09117j">N09 (VI.B.1)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n09all.htm#n09117j"> 117(j)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> filiusfamilius</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">&ldquo;Roman Law&rdquo;: It might happen that a marriage was fruitless, or that a man saw all his sons go to the grave before him, and that the <i>paterfamilias</i> had thus to face the prospect of the extinction of his family and of his own descent to the tomb without posterity to make him blessed. To obviate so dire a misfortune, he resorted to the practice of adoption, so common in India and Greece. If it was a <i>paterfamilias</i> that he adopted, the process was called adrogation (<i>adrogatio</i>); if it was a <mark><i>filiusfamilias</i></mark> it was simply <i>adoptio</i>. <small> <cite a>&ldquo;ROMAN LAW&rdquo;</cite></a> <a name="EBRL1" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#EBRL1"><cite title="source">Encyclopaedia Britannica</cite></a>, 11th edit. (1911) XXIII p. 530</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Raphael transcription: <a name="c03138f" href="c3all.htm#c03138f">VI.C.03:138(f)</a> </mm></dd> </dd></dl>
